  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I stop Outlook from synchronising folders automatically?",
  "response": "To stop Microsoft Outlook from synchronizing folders automatically, you can adjust the settings for your account. Here are some steps you can follow, depending on the version of Outlook you are using:\n\n### For Outlook 365 / Outlook 2019 / Outlook 2016:\n\n1. **Open Outlook**: Start the Outlook application.\n\n2. **File Menu**: Click on the \"File\" tab in the upper left corner.\n\n3. **Account Settings**: Select \"Account Settings,\" then again click on \"Account Settings\" from the dropdown.\n\n4. **Change Account**: In the Account Settings window, select the account you want to modify and click on \"Change.\"\n\n5. **More Settings**: In the Change Account window, click on \"More Settings.\"\n\n6. **Advanced Tab**: Navigate to the \"Advanced\" tab.\n\n7. **Uncheck Options**: Here, you can find options related to folder synchronization. You can uncheck options like \"Download Shared Folders\" if they are checked. Another option to consider is under the \"Cached Exchange Mode Settings,\" you can adjust how much mail to keep offline, but this primarily affects how much older mail is synced rather than stopping sync entirely.\n\n8. **Close and Save**: Click on \"OK,\" then \"Next,\" and finally \"Finish\" to save your changes, then close out of the Account Settings window.\n\n9. **Restart Outlook**: Restart Outlook to ensure the settings take effect.\n\n### For Outlook 2013 and Earlier Versions:\n\nThe steps are similar, but you may have to navigate slightly different menu options. The essential principles remain the same: you want to access your Account Settings and find options related to synchronization.\n\n### For IMAP Accounts:\n\nIf you are using an IMAP account, you can manage synchronization settings for individual folders:\n\n1. **Right-click on the Folder**: Right-click on the folder you want to stop synchronizing (e.g., Inbox) and select \"Properties.\"\n\n2. **General Tab**: Go to the \"General\" tab.\n\n3. **Unlimited/Only Download Headers**: In some versions, there may be a setting for \"Download headers only.\" If you find this option, select it to limit the synchronization.\n\n4. **OK**: Click \"OK\" to save the changes.\n\n### Additional Considerations:\n\n- **Work Offline**: If you want to stop all synchronization temporarily, you can use the \"Work Offline\" feature. Go to the \"Send/Receive\" tab and click on \"Work Offline.\" This will disconnect Outlook from the server until you decide to work online again.\n\n- **Disable Syncing for Specific Folders**: Unfortunately, Outlook does not provide a granular way to stop syncing specific folders unless you are using Cached Exchange Mode with an Exchange account.\n\nBy following these instructions, you can minimize or stop Outlook from synchronizing folders automatically. If you encounter any specific issues or inconsistencies, providing more details about your Outlook version and account type can help in offering more tailored advice.",
